  "prompt": "How much bandwidth per MH does scrypt mining use?",
  "response": "The bandwidth usage of scrypt mining per megahash (MH) largely depends on factors like the mining pool protocol, network settings, and specific user setups. However, compared to the computational aspect, the actual bandwidth usage for scrypt mining is relatively low. Typically, in most mining setups, traffic primarily consists of:\n\n1. Submitting shares: Miners frequently communicate with the mining pool to submit valid shares.\n2. Receiving work updates: Miners also receive new work units from the pool.\n\nFor reference, scrypt mining could use only a few kilobytes per second of bandwidth for submitting shares and receiving work. For precise figures, a typical scrypt miner might use between 500 KB to 1 MB per hour. Therefore, even with a reasonably high hash rate, like several MH/s, bandwidth usage remains modest. It's always a good idea to check with your specific mining pool, as they sometimes publish exact bandwidth requirements based on their protocol and setup.",
